      modelAnswer: 'The nervous system consists of the central nervous system (brain and spinal cord) and the peripheral nervous system (nerves connecting the CNS to the rest of the body). It enables rapid response by transmitting electrical impulses along specialised cells called neurones. Sensory receptors detect a stimulus — for example, heat receptors in the skin detecting a hot surface, or light receptors in the retina detecting light. The receptor sends an impulse along a sensory neurone to the CNS. In a reflex action (such as pulling the hand away from a hot object), the impulse passes through a relay neurone in the spinal cord directly to a motor neurone, which carries the impulse to an effector (a muscle or gland). This pathway, called a reflex arc, takes a fraction of a second and does not need the brain — making it essential for protecting the body from harm. In voluntary actions, the impulse goes via the brain for processing and conscious decision-making. Synapses between neurones use neurotransmitters, slowing transmission slightly but allowing summation and inhibition of signals. Myelination of axons speeds up impulse transmission considerably. Together, these features allow the nervous system to coordinate rapid, precise responses essential for survival.'
