      modelAnswer: 'Natural selection is the process by which individuals with characteristics best suited to their environment are more likely to survive and reproduce, passing on their genes. Three conditions are required: variation (individuals differ), heritability (variation can be passed on), and selection pressure (the environment favours some variations over others). Over generations, advantageous alleles become more common — the population becomes adapted to its environment. A classic example is the peppered moth in 19th-century Britain. Most moths were light and well camouflaged on lichen-covered tree bark. Industrial pollution killed the lichen and blackened the bark with soot, so light moths became visible to bird predators while a rare dark variety became better camouflaged. More dark moths survived and reproduced, passing the dark allele to offspring. Within decades, the proportion of dark moths in industrial areas rose to over 90%, while light moths still dominated unpolluted areas. When clean-air laws reduced pollution, light moths regained their advantage and their frequency rose. Other examples include antibiotic resistance in bacteria, pesticide resistance in insects, beak shape changes in Galápagos finches in response to drought, and rapid evolution of flu and COVID-19 viruses. Evidence for natural selection comes from the fossil record, comparative anatomy, embryology and DNA evidence. Natural selection therefore produces adaptation — populations become better suited to their environment over generations — and underlies the diversity of life on Earth.'
