      modelAnswer: 'Blood glucose concentration is controlled by negative feedback involving the pancreas. After eating, blood glucose rises; the pancreas detects this and beta cells secrete insulin. Insulin binds receptors on liver and muscle cells, triggering them to take up glucose and convert it to glycogen for storage. Blood glucose falls back to normal. When blood glucose falls (fasting, exercise), alpha cells secrete glucagon, which causes the liver to break glycogen back into glucose and release it into the blood, raising blood glucose. The two hormones are antagonistic and the system is self-correcting. Failure leads to diabetes. In type 1 diabetes, the pancreas does not produce enough insulin (often because the immune system has destroyed beta cells); blood glucose rises uncontrollably. Symptoms include thirst, frequent urination, weight loss and tiredness. Treatment requires insulin injections matched to carbohydrate intake. In type 2 diabetes, target cells become resistant to insulin, often linked to obesity and inactivity; the pancreas at first produces more insulin but eventually cannot keep up. Treatment is initially diet and exercise, then drugs and sometimes insulin. Untreated diabetes can damage blood vessels, eyes, kidneys and nerves, demonstrating why glucose homeostasis is essential. The rapid rise of type 2 diabetes globally reflects changes in diet and lifestyle and is a major public health priority.'
