      modelAnswer: 'All three are blood vessels but differ in structure to match function. Arteries carry blood at high pressure away from the heart; they have thick muscular walls with much elastic tissue that stretches and recoils, smoothing pressure surges, and a small lumen. Smaller arteries (arterioles) have proportionally more muscle, allowing fine control of blood flow. Veins return blood at low pressure to the heart; they have thinner walls, less elastic tissue, wider lumens, and contain semi-lunar valves to prevent backflow as blood is helped along by skeletal muscle squeezing. Capillaries are the exchange vessels: their walls are only one cell thick (single endothelial cells), giving the shortest possible diffusion distance, and the narrow lumen (just wider than a red blood cell) slows blood flow and brings cells close to tissues. Capillary networks are highly branched, giving an enormous surface area. Each vessel type matches its job: arteries deliver high-pressure flow, capillaries enable exchange, veins provide a return route.'
