      modelAnswer: 'The nitrogen cycle moves nitrogen between the atmosphere, soil, plants, animals and decomposers. Atmospheric nitrogen (N₂) is unreactive and most organisms cannot use it directly. Nitrogen-fixing bacteria convert N₂ to ammonium (NH₄⁺); some live freely in soil (e.g. Azotobacter), others in nodules on the roots of legumes (Rhizobium) in a symbiotic relationship — the bacteria fix nitrogen for the plant in exchange for sugars. Nitrifying bacteria oxidise ammonium to nitrites (Nitrosomonas) and then to nitrates (Nitrobacter); plants absorb nitrates from soil through their roots and use them to make amino acids and nucleic acids. Animals obtain nitrogen by eating plants or other animals; their wastes (urea) and dead bodies are broken down by decomposers (saprotrophic bacteria and fungi) which release ammonium back into the soil — the process of decomposition or ammonification. Denitrifying bacteria in waterlogged anaerobic soils convert nitrates back to N₂, returning nitrogen to the atmosphere. Lightning also fixes some nitrogen in the atmosphere. The Haber process artificially fixes nitrogen for fertilisers, adding huge amounts of reactive nitrogen to ecosystems. Bacteria are central to the cycle: without nitrogen-fixing bacteria, plants would not have nitrogen for proteins; without nitrifying bacteria, ammonium would not be converted to a usable form; without decomposers, dead matter would accumulate and lock up nitrogen; without denitrifying bacteria, atmospheric nitrogen levels would be reduced. Farmers exploit this knowledge by rotating crops with legumes to maintain soil nitrogen naturally, using fertilisers carefully to avoid eutrophication of waterways, and aerating soil to favour nitrifying over denitrifying bacteria.'
