      modelAnswer: 'Pesticides are chemicals used to kill pests that damage crops. Advantages: rapid action, can be applied widely, often very effective in the short term. Disadvantages: may kill non-target species (e.g. bees, beneficial insects), reducing biodiversity; can persist in the environment and accumulate up food chains (bioaccumulation, as DDT did, threatening predators); pests can evolve resistance, requiring stronger or more frequent applications; residues on food are a health concern; can pollute water. Biological control uses a natural predator, parasite or pathogen of the pest. Examples include ladybirds eating aphids, parasitic wasps controlling caterpillars, and BT bacteria producing toxins lethal to specific pests. Advantages: targets only the pest, leaves other species unaffected; once established, often self-sustaining without repeated application; reduces chemical use; pests rarely evolve resistance to predators. Disadvantages: slower to act; introduced biological controls can themselves become invasive (e.g. cane toads in Australia); may not give complete pest control. Modern integrated pest management combines methods: biological control as the main approach, with selective pesticide use only when needed, and cultural practices like crop rotation. This balances effective pest control with minimal environmental impact, supporting sustainable agriculture.'
